          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here are 3 approaches for decoupling the bubble menu. Each one addresses a different point on the spectrum between ease-of-use and customizability.\n\n---\n\n## Current State (what we're decoupling from)\n\nThe bubble menu in `dashboard/src/components/editor-v2/ui/bubble-menu/` has these Resend-specific dependencies:\n- `@/lib/cn` (className merging utility)\n- `@/ui/shared` dropdown styles (in `node-selector.tsx`)\n- `@/ui/icons/icon-variable` + `@/ui/toast` (in `link-selector.tsx`)\n- `VariablesDropdown` from `plugins/variables/dropdown` (in `link-selector.tsx`)\n- `VARIABLE_PATTERN` from `@/utils/templates/extract-template-variables`\n- `EDITOR_CONTENT_ID` from legacy editor\n- Hardcoded Tailwind classes using Resend's design tokens (`gray-10`, `gray-a2`, `bg-background`, etc.)\n\n---\n\n## Approach 1: Compound Component API (Radix-inspired)\n\n**Inspiration**: Radix UI primitives - unstyled, composable, accessible building blocks.\n\n```tsx\nimport { BubbleMenu } from '@react-email/editor';\n\n// Zero-config default (works out of the box)\n<BubbleMenu.Root />\n\n// Full customization via compound components\n<BubbleMenu.Root>\n  <BubbleMenu.NodeSelector />\n  <BubbleMenu.LinkSelector>\n    {/* Plugin slot: render custom content inside the link input */}\n    <MyVariablesButton />\n  </BubbleMenu.LinkSelector>\n  <BubbleMenu.Separator />\n  <BubbleMenu.Group>\n    <BubbleMenu.Bold />\n    <BubbleMenu.Italic />\n    <BubbleMenu.Underline />\n  </BubbleMenu.Group>\n  <BubbleMenu.Separator />\n  <BubbleMenu.Group>\n    <BubbleMenu.AlignLeft />\n    <BubbleMenu.AlignCenter />\n    <BubbleMenu.AlignRight />\n  </BubbleMenu.Group>\n</BubbleMenu.Root>\n\n// Custom item\n<BubbleMenu.Item\n  name=\"highlight\"\n  icon={HighlightIcon}\n  isActive={() => editor.isActive('highlight')}\n  command={() => editor.chain().focus().toggleHighlight().run()}\n/>\n```\n\n**How styling works**: Ships with no styles. Exports `data-*` attributes for each state (`data-active`, `data-open`). Users bring their own CSS/Tailwind.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Maximum composability - users pick exactly which items to show\n- Plugin slot pattern for `LinkSelector` children handles variable dropdown elegantly\n- Each sub-component can be individually replaced or extended\n- `<BubbleMenu.Root />` with zero children = sensible defaults (like Radix `<Select>` with no custom trigger)\n- Familiar API for anyone who's used Radix\n\n**Cons**:\n- More verbose for the common case\n- Users must understand the component tree to customize\n- Unstyled by default means more work for basic users - the \"it works but looks terrible\" problem\n- Harder to maintain backward compatibility as we add features\n\n---\n\n## Approach 2: Headless Hook + Default Component (Base UI-inspired)\n\n**Inspiration**: Base UI / Headless UI - hooks that give you state/logic, optional default render.\n\n```tsx\nimport {\n  useBubbleMenu,\n  BubbleMenu,\n  BubbleMenuContent,\n} from '@react-email/editor';\n\n// Zero-config (uses default unstyled component)\n<BubbleMenu />\n\n// With className overrides (like Base UI's `className` prop accepting function)\n<BubbleMenu\n  className=\"my-bubble-menu\"\n  slotProps={{\n    item: { className: 'my-item' },\n    separator: { className: 'my-separator' },\n    nodeSelector: { className: 'my-selector' },\n    linkSelector: {\n      className: 'my-link-input',\n      children: <MyVariablesButton />, // plugin slot\n    },\n  }}\n/>\n\n// Full headless mode: use the hook, render your own UI\nfunction MyCustomBubbleMenu() {\n  const { items, alignmentItems, nodeSelector, linkSelector } = useBubbleMenu();\n\n  return (\n    <BubbleMenuContent> {/* handles positioning via TipTap */}\n      <div className=\"my-toolbar\">\n        {items.map(item => (\n          <button\n            key={item.name}\n            onClick={item.command}\n            data-active={item.isActive()}\n          >\n            <item.icon />\n          </button>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </BubbleMenuContent>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n**How styling works**: Ships with minimal functional CSS (positioning, visibility). All visual styles via `className` / `slotProps`. The hook gives raw data + commands.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simplest zero-config experience - `<BubbleMenu />` just works\n- `slotProps` pattern allows targeted styling without rewriting the component tree\n- `useBubbleMenu()` hook gives full escape hatch for power users\n- Clean separation: logic in hooks, rendering optional\n- Plugin slot via `slotProps.linkSelector.children` is straightforward\n\n**Cons**:\n- `slotProps` can get nested/complex for deep customization\n- Less composable than compound components for structural changes (reordering items, wrapping groups)\n- Two mental models (component vs hook) to maintain and document\n\n---\n\n## Approach 3: Configurable Component + Copy-Paste Recipes (shadcn/ui-inspired)\n\n**Inspiration**: shadcn/ui - ship a well-styled default component with copy-paste recipes for customization.\n\n```tsx\nimport { BubbleMenu } from '@react-email/editor';\n\n// Zero-config with built-in default styles (Tailwind)\n<BubbleMenu />\n\n// Override via className (merges with defaults)\n<BubbleMenu className=\"rounded-lg shadow-2xl\" />\n\n// Omit specific items\n<BubbleMenu omit={['Uppercase', 'Code', 'Align Right']} />\n\n// Plugin slot for link selector extras\n<BubbleMenu\n  linkSelector={{\n    extraActions: <MyVariablesButton />,\n  }}\n/>\n\n// Add custom items\n<BubbleMenu\n  extraItems={[\n    {\n      name: 'Highlight',\n      icon: HighlightIcon,\n      isActive: () => editor.isActive('highlight'),\n      command: () => editor.chain().focus().toggleHighlight().run(),\n    },\n  ]}\n/>\n```\n\nFor deep customization, docs provide a \"copy this component\" recipe (like shadcn/ui's `npx shadcn-ui@latest add button` philosophy but without the CLI):\n\n```\n// docs/recipes/bubble-menu.tsx\n// Copy this file into your project and customize freely\n```\n\n**How styling works**: Ships with Tailwind classes using CSS custom properties for theming. Users override via `className` or CSS variables:\n\n```css\n[data-email-editor] {\n  --re-bubble-bg: white;\n  --re-bubble-border: #e5e7eb;\n  --re-bubble-item-hover: #f3f4f6;\n  --re-bubble-item-active: #e5e7eb;\n}\n```\n\n**Pros**:\n- Best zero-config DX - looks good immediately with Tailwind\n- `omit` prop is the simplest API for removing items (already exists in current code)\n- `extraItems` / `linkSelector.extraActions` for common extensions\n- CSS custom properties enable theming without touching component code\n- Copy-paste recipe for when props aren't enough\n- Lowest learning curve\n\n**Cons**:\n- Tailwind dependency for default styles (or need to ship both)\n- CSS variables approach is limited compared to full component replacement\n- Copy-paste recipe = diverging fork that doesn't get updates\n- Less elegant escape hatch compared to hooks or compound components\n\n---\n\n## My Recommendation: Approach 2 (Headless Hook + Default Component)\n\nReasoning:\n\n1. **Best of both worlds**: `<BubbleMenu />` for quick start, `useBubbleMenu()` for full control. No middle ground that's \"kinda customizable but not really.\"\n\n2. **No styling opinion shipped**: Avoids the Tailwind dependency debate entirely. The default component renders semantic HTML with `data-*` attributes. Users style however they want.\n\n3. **Plugin slot is natural**: `slotProps.linkSelector.children` for the variables dropdown maps cleanly to how Resend consumes it internally.\n\n4. **Matches Base UI's trajectory**: Base UI (MUI's headless library) has proven this pattern works at scale. It's also what the React ecosystem is moving toward.\n\n5. **Dashboard consumption is clean**: Resend's dashboard would use `<BubbleMenu slotProps={{ linkSelector: { children: <VariablesDropdown /> } }} className=\"...\" />` and add its own Tailwind classes.\n\n6. **`@react-email/editor` already ships TipTap as a dependency** - the hook naturally lives alongside the extensions.\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved Questions\n\n1. Should the default `<BubbleMenu />` render the `NodeSelector` dropdown (text/h1/h2/h3/list/quote/code)? It uses `@radix-ui/react-popover` currently - adds a dependency to the editor package.\n\n2. The link-selector has complex behavior (escape to cancel, click-outside to submit, `#` placeholder cleanup). Should this logic ship in the hook or only in the default component?\n\n3. CSS: Should the package ship a minimal optional CSS file for positioning/transitions, or should everything be inline styles + data attributes?",
