          "text": "Good question. Let me show you exactly what the NodeSelector is.\n\nThe **NodeSelector** is the dropdown at the left edge of the bubble menu that lets you change the block type of the selected text. When you select some text, it shows the current block type (e.g., \"Text\", \"Title\", \"Heading\") with a chevron, and clicking it opens a dropdown with these options:\n\n- **Text** (paragraph)\n- **Title** (H1)\n- **Subtitle** (H2)\n- **Heading** (H3)\n- **Bullet List**\n- **Numbered List**\n- **Quote**\n- **Code**\n\nYou can see it in `dashboard/src/components/editor-v2/ui/bubble-menu/node-selector.tsx`. Here's the relevant rendering part:\n\n```tsx\n// The trigger shows the active block type name + chevron\n<Popover.Trigger className=\"...\">\n  <span>{activeItem?.name}</span>    // e.g. \"Text\", \"Title\"\n  <ChevronDown className=\"h-4 w-4\" />\n</Popover.Trigger>\n\n// The content is a dropdown list of block types\n<Popover.Content className={cn('mt-1', dropdown.content.sizing, dropdown.content.appearance)}>\n  {filteredItems.map((item) => (\n    <button className={cn(dropdown.item.appearance.gray, dropdown.item.sizing)}>\n      <item.icon />           // e.g. Heading1, TextIcon\n      <span>{item.name}</span>\n      {activeItem.name === item.name && <Check />}  // checkmark on active\n    </button>\n  ))}\n</Popover.Content>\n```\n\nThe `dropdown.content.sizing`, `dropdown.content.appearance`, `dropdown.item.appearance.gray`, and `dropdown.item.sizing` are all imported from `@/ui/shared` - these are Resend's design system tokens that define the dropdown's visual look (padding, background, hover states, border radius, etc.).\n\n**The question is**: in the open-source version, this becomes an unstyled `<Popover.Content>` with unstyled `<button>` elements inside it. Should we:\n\n**Option A - Leave entirely unstyled**: The dropdown renders with zero visual styles. It'll be a plain white box with plain text buttons, no padding, no hover states. Users must add all styling via `className` or their own CSS targeting `data-*` attributes.\n\n**Option B - Ship a minimal optional CSS file**: Something like `@react-email/editor/styles.css` that handles functional layout only (flexbox for the item rows, basic gap/padding so items don't collapse on each other, popover positioning). No colors, no borders, no hover states - just enough structure that the dropdown is usable.\n\nThink of it like this:\n- Option A = Radix Primitives (truly naked)\n- Option B = Radix Primitives + their \"functional\" CSS that ships with `@radix-ui/react-popover` (handles transform-origin, positioning, will-change, etc.)",
