xt.js App Router pages/layouts and `api/` route handlers.\n- `src/db/` - Drizzle schema and clients (`main`, `email-events`, `logs`).\n- `src/lib/` - integrations and shared services (Inngest, AWS, analytics, logging).\n- `transactional/emails/` - React Email templates.\n- `e2e/` - Playwright end-to-end tests.\n\n## First 5 Minutes In Repo\n\n1. Scan `package.json` scripts for the task command.\n2. Read `src/actions/safe-action.ts` to understand action clients and server error handling.\n3. Read `src/env.ts` to understand required environment variables and validation.\n4. Read `src/server/user.ts` to understand auth context (`getUser`) used by authenticated actions.\n5. Read `src/lib/inngest.ts` to understand event contracts and background-job surface area.\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\n### Tech Stack\n- **Framework**: Next.js 16 with App Router and React 19\n- **Language**: TypeScript with strict mode\n- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS v4\n- **Database**: PostgreSQL with Drizzle ORM\n- **Authentication**: Supabase\n- **Email**: Resend API with React Email templates\n- **Background Jobs**: Inngest\n- **Server Actions**: next-safe-action with Zod validation\n- **Testing**: Vitest (unit), Playwright (E2E)\n- **Linting/Formatting**: Biome\n- **Environment**: Doppler for secrets management\n- **Package Manager**: pnpm\n\n## Core Patterns To Follow\n\n- Prefer `next-safe-action` for server mutations.\n- Use `authActionClient` for authenticated actions, `baseActionClient` for public actions, and `withBotProtection` where bot protection is required.\n- Pair action and schema domains: `src/actions/foo.ts` with `src/schemas/foo.ts`.\n- Keep action handlers thin; move complex logic to `src/server/`.\n- Use `UserFacingError` for user-visible failures.\n- Use `@/` absolute imports.\n\n## Database and ORM\n\n- Use Drizzle ORM for all database operations. Schema and clients live in `src/db/`.\n- Avoid N+1 queries. Prefer batch selects and joins over querying inside loops.\n- Use `dbReadReplica1` from `src/db/main` for read-heavy operations to reduce load on the primary. Be mindful of small replication delays — use the primary `db` when reading data that was just written.\n- Prefer batch inserts (`db.insert(...).values([...])`) over inserting rows one at a time in a loop.\n- Use Drizzle's relational query API or explicit joins instead of manually fetching related data in separate queries.\n\n## React Component Guidelines\n\n- Prefer **React Server Components** (RSC) by default. Components should remain server components unless they require interactivity.\n- When interactivity is needed (event handlers, hooks, browser APIs), mark the **lowest possible component** in the tree with `'use client'` — never higher than necessary.\n- Extract interactive parts into small, focused client components and keep the parent tree as server components.\n- Prefer `import * as React from \"react\";` over named imports from `react`.\n- Avoid using `useCallback` and `useMemo` for caching by default.\n- Only add `useCallback`/`useMemo` when there is a demonstrated, real performance issue.\n\n## Code Comments\n\n- Avoid adding code comments unless absolutely necessary.\n- Only add comments for genuinely complex business logic that would be difficult to understand from the code alone.\n- Well-named variables, functions, and types should be preferred over comments.\n- Do not add comments that simply restate what the code does.\n- Do not add comments to mark code sections\n\n\n## Test Guidelines\n\n- Test names should describe the exact assertion or behavior being verified.\n- Do not use \"should\" or \"should not\" in test names.\n- Prefer direct names like `\"updates a user when organization details change\"`.\n- Avoid wrapping tests in a high-level `describe` block when the file exports only one function.\n- Use `describe` only when grouping multiple functions or distinct use-case groups.\n\n### Vitest and Playwright\n\nAlways write tests. Use this to pick which kind:\n\nVitest = fast, isolated correctness. Use for logic, helpers, individual (or small nested subset of) React components, and server code including Server Actions (call directly; fake/mock as needed).\n\nPlaywright = user-visible, real-world correctness. Use for critical flows, client↔server wiring, Server Actions via UI (true integration wiring).\n\n## Copywriting\n\n- Use sentence case for in-app UI copy.\n- Do not use title case in the app UI.\n- Apply this convention to CTAs, buttons, headings, labels, and similar interface text.\n\n## PR instructions\n\n- Commits and titles are lowercase only\n- Use prefixes like feat, fix, chore, refactor. Followed by colon (:). i.e.: \"feat: add new auth method\"\n- Always run `pnpm lint`, `pnpm typecheck` before committing.\n- Always run `pnpm test` after making changes.\n\n</system-reminder>",
