          "text": "Not much, honestly. Here's what it would take:\n\n**1. Move tiptap from `dependencies` to `peerDependencies`**\n\n```json\n\"peerDependencies\": {\n  \"@tiptap/core\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/react\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/pm\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/starter-kit\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/extension-code-block\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/extension-heading\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/extension-horizontal-rule\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/extension-placeholder\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  \"@tiptap/html\": \"^3.17.1\",\n  // existing peers...\n  \"@radix-ui/react-popover\": \"^1.0.0\",\n  \"lucide-react\": \">=0.300.0\",\n  \"react\": \"^18.0 || ^19.0 || ^19.0.0-rc\"\n}\n```\n\n**2. Add them as devDependencies for local development/testing**\n\nThe monorepo's own `packages/editor` needs tiptap installed to build and run tests. Standard pattern: peer + dev.\n\n**3. That's it.**\n\nNo code changes needed — the imports stay the same, the API stays the same. The only difference is that npm/pnpm stops bundling tiptap inside the package and instead expects the consumer to provide it.\n\n**Tradeoff:** The DX gets slightly worse — consumers need to install 9 tiptap packages themselves instead of just `@react-email/editor`. That's why libraries like `slate` and `prosemirror` ship wrapper packages that re-export from their core. But since our consumers (the dashboard) already install tiptap directly, this is a non-issue in practice.\n\nWant me to do it in this PR?",
